04302nam a22006615i 9780292773004DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211980txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927730047 a10.7560/7702252doi  a(DE-B1597)587424  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHB99.5b.G67 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a330.15/51 aGordon, Wendell, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInstitutional Economics :bThe Changing System /cWendell Gordon. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1980  a1 online resource (364 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- tPART I Institutional Theory and Comparative Theory -- t2. The Institutional Theory of Economic Progress: Technology and Institutions -- t3. The Value Theory of Institutional Economics -- t4. Other Concepts of Value -- t5. Microeconomics and Decision Making -- t6. Macroeconomics and Decision Making -- t7. Dynamic Economic Process -- t8. Marxian and Other "Radical" Theories -- tPART II Research Methods -- t9. Research Methods -- tPART III Case Studies and Policy -- t10. The Institution of Property -- t11. The Limited-Liability Corporation -- t12. Government and Business -- t13. The Multinationals -- t14. The Energy-Ecology "Crisis" of the 1970s -- t15. The Monetary System -- t16. Inflation -- t17. The Job Guarantee -- t18. The Larger Picture -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWendell Gordon presents the philosophy of economic institutionalism clearly and evocatively, in the tradition of the pragmatism of Peirce, James, and Dewey. In Gordon's view, the institutionalism of Veblen and Ayres, the only indigenous American school of economic thought, offered the most hope for understanding and solving the economic problems of the twentieth century. The institutional approach—long known as the Texas School—looks at social order as ongoing process. The effort to explain how our attitudes have developed and how they are changed is central to this approach. Gordon argues that the dynamics of technical change, the institutionalism of behavior norms, human biology, and the resource endowment of the universe interact to create and change these attitudes. Gordon thoroughly analyzes both orthodox and Marxist economic approaches with regard to institutional economics. He also examines such other radical approaches as underconsumption and the single tax. There is a discussion of the procedures and problems involved in testing for the validity of institutional theory and the analysis of economic problems in the institutional frame of reference. In addition, inflation, energy, multinationals, property rights, business organization, unemployment, and other issues are considered from an institutional perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEconomics. 0aInstitutional economics. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292773004423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292773004/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK